    "info": {
      "english_name": "Lean 4 Theorem Prover and Programming Language — compilation pipeline",
      "summary": "Lean 4 is a dependently typed theorem prover and general-purpose programming language whose compiler is written almost entirely in Lean 4 itself, with only a small trusted C++ kernel. Source text flows through a user-extensible parser and macro expander, a metavariable-based bidirectional elaborator, an independent kernel type checker, and an LCNF-based code generator that emits C.",
      "description": "Lean 4's defining architectural choice is extensibility at every stage combined with a minimal trusted computing base. The Pratt-style parser is driven by syntax categories and user-declared notations, so `syntax`/`macro_rules` declarations extend the grammar of the language being compiled while it is compiled; macro expansion is hygienic, with scopes attached to Syntax nodes so generated binders cannot capture user names. The elaborator turns Syntax into Expr (terms of a Calculus of Inductive Constructions with impredicative Prop, definitional proof irrelevance and quotient types), running bidirectionally against expected types, postponing unsolved goals in a metavariable context, discharging instance goals via tabled type-class resolution, and delegating equality to a definitional-unfolding unifier. Tactics are simply metaprograms in the same language that manipulate the same metavariable context.",
      "facts": [
        {"label": "First stable release", "value": "Lean 4.0.0, September 2023 (project announced 2021)"},
        {"label": "Trusted kernel size", "value": "~6,000 lines of C++ — the only part that must be trusted"},
        {"label": "Bootstrapping", "value": "Parser, elaborator, tactics and code generator are written in Lean 4"},
        {"label": "Core type theory", "value": "CIC + impredicative Prop, definitional proof irrelevance, quotient types"},
        {"label": "Parser", "value": "Pratt parser over user-extensible syntax categories"},
        {"label": "Macro hygiene", "value": "Scope-annotated Syntax nodes; macro_rules cannot capture binders"},
        {"label": "Back-end IR", "value": "LCNF (Lean Compiler Normal Form), A-normal/CPS-style with type erasure"},
        {"label": "Code generation target", "value": "C source, compiled by clang/LLVM; interpreter path shares the same environment"},
        {"label": "Memory management", "value": "Non-deferred reference counting; RC=1 enables destructive in-place update (FBIP)"},
        {"label": "Module format", "value": ".olean files, memory-mapped for fast import of compiled environments"}
      ],
      "sources": [
        {"title": "The Lean 4 Theorem Prover and Programming Language (CADE-28, 2021)", "url": "https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-79876-5_37"},
